          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">French Presidential hopeful convicted </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/marine-le-pen-court-storms-out-sentenced-four-years-jail-embezzlement.png" alt="Marine Le Pen storms out of court after being sentenced to four years in jail for embezzlement" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Marine Le Pen storms out of court after being sentenced to four years in jail for embezzlement. Credits: Independent</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          A French court <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-04-2025-h1-1-convicted-marine-le-pen" target="_blank">convicted Marine Le Pen</a>, leader of the far-right National Rally (RN) party, of embezzling European Union funds. She received a four-year prison sentence, including two years with an electronic tag and the other two suspended (subject to breach of conditions). Le Pen is immediately barred from seeking public office for five years, rendering her ineligible to run in the 2027 presidential election.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The court found that Le Pen and her 24 co-defendants misused funds of over $4.5M designated for European parliamentary aides. The funds were redirected to pay RN party staff between 2004 and 2016. ​Other defendants include former Members of the European Parliament (MEPs) and parliamentary assistants. Le Pen plans to appeal the conviction.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          This conviction significantly impacts France's political landscape, particularly the far-right movement. Jordan Bardella, Le Pen's protégé, condemned the ruling as unjust and detrimental to French democracy. Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán supported Le Pen, posting "<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-04-2025-h1-2-je-suis-marine" target="_blank">Je suis Marine!</a>" on social media.</p>
        </mj-text>
