    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="10px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇺🇸 Trump’s “Liberation Day” tariffs</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Trump has quoted April 2 as “<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-04-2025-br2-8-liberation-day" target="_blank">Liberation Day</a>” and promised to launch his next wave of import tariffs, including 25% tariffs on all imports from countries that buy oil from Venezuela and 25% on auto imports with taxes on fully imported cars. Trump suggested that tariffs be levied on the European Union, South Korea, Brazil, and India, among other countries.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Trump expects to raise $100B in annual revenue from this initiative. He has already <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-04-2025-br2-9-launched-many-tariffs" target="_blank">launched many tariffs</a> that have impacted global trade. Reciprocal tariffs will ensue, which might lead to a broader trade war. While the Trump administration seems optimistic about the measure, economists suggest it will upend the global supply chain and increase consumer prices.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
